    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-07-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-07-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="310"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d310">
                <head>310. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_FMV1" type="from">Michael V.
                        Forrestal</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to President
                        <persName corresp="#p_KJF1" type="to">Kennedy</persName>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d310fn0">Source: Kennedy Library, National
                        Security Files, Meetings and Memoranda Series, Staff Memoranda, <persName
                            corresp="#p_FMV1">M.V. Forrestal</persName>, 11/62-11/63. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-07-03">July 3, 1963</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">FAR EAST ROUNDUP</p>
                <p>[Here follow sections on South Vietnam (for text, see <ref
                        target="frus1961-63v03">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1961–1963, volume III, pages
                        447-449) and Laos.</ref>]</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Korea</hi>
                </p>
                <p>The immediate problem in Korea is the shortfall in the current harvest, which
                    amounts to approximately half a million tons of grain.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d310fn1">The Department of State sent <persName corresp="#p_BMG1"
                            >McGeorge Bundy</persName> a memorandum explaining the grain crisis and
                        the measures to cope with it. (Memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_BWH1"
                            >Brubeck</persName> to <persName>Bundy</persName>, June 19; Department
                        of State, Central Files, <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> (US) 15-9 S
                        KOR) <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_HRJ1">Hilsman</persName> and later <persName
                            corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1"
                            >McNamara</persName> discussed the grain shortage problem on June 28,
                        agreeing that the situation was worthy of U.S. action to alleviate it.
                        (Memoranda of telephone conversations, June 28; Kennedy Library, <persName
                            corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName> Papers, Telephone Conversations,
                        Korea)</note> After some bureaucratic delay we have succeeded in making
                    approximately $8,500,000 worth (about 160,000 tons) of grain available to the
                    Koreans. It will be nip and tuck whether the food arrives in Korea in time to
                    avert real shortages, and we have suggested strongly to the Japanese that they
                    make an interim contribution of rice. The Japanese have agreed to contribute
                    40,000 tons.</p>
                <p>Over Agriculture’s objections, we allowed this emergency shipment to go forward
                    under the current <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> 480 agreement which provides
                        <pb facs="0688" n="652" xml:id="pg_652"/> that only 10 percent of the local
                    currency proceeds be devoted to U.S. uses. I have told Agriculture and Treasury
                    that we would support them in an overall review of South Korean’s dollar
                    position when a new <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> 480 agreement is
                    negotiated this fall with a view to seeing whether we can increase the U.S.-use
                    percentage.</p>
                <p>The two American captains whose helicopter landed in North Korea near the
                    Demarcation Line are alive but have not been released. Having exhausted
                    diplomatic channels, we are beginning to take retaliatory action. We have asked
                    Japan to deny North Korea any transit rights. Similar and increasingly severe
                    measures are planned.</p>
                <p>[Here follow sections on Indonesia, the Philippines, and Thailand.]</p>
            </div>
